First, we need to find the symmetric difference A △ B. The symmetric difference is the set of elements which are in either of the sets A or B, but not in their intersection.

A △ B = (A ∪ B) - (A ∩ B)

A ∪ B = {3, 5, 7, 9, 10}
A ∩ B = {5, 7}

A △ B = {3, 9, 10}

Now, we need to find the intersection of (A △ B) with the set {5, 7}.

(A △ B) ∩ {5, 7} = {3, 9, 10} ∩ {5, 7} = ∅ (empty set)

Now, let's verify the distributive property of the symmetric difference over intersection:

A △ (B ∩ {5, 7}) = A △ ({5, 7})

(A △ {5, 7}) = ({3, 5, 7, 9} △ {5, 7}) = {3, 9}

(B △ {5, 7}) = ({5, 7, 10} △ {5, 7}) = {10}

Now, we need to find the intersection of the two sets:

(A △ {5, 7}) ∩ (B △ {5, 7}) = {3, 9} ∩ {10} = ∅ (empty set)

Thus, the distributive property of the symmetric difference over intersection holds true:

(A △ B) ∩ {5, 7} = A △ (B ∩ {5, 7})
